1
00:00:00,200 --> 00:00:04,939
In this video we are going to explain microservices characteristics.

2
00:00:06,150 --> 00:00:09,180
Again, we will refer to Martin Fowler article.

3
00:00:09,180 --> 00:00:15,000
There are some common characteristics for microservice architecture that explain in the Martin Fowler

4
00:00:15,000 --> 00:00:20,670
article, and Martin Fowler explained these characteristics in these captions.

5
00:00:20,670 --> 00:00:24,810
You can see the first one is Componentization via services.

6
00:00:24,810 --> 00:00:31,710
Component is a unit of software that is independently replaceable and upgradable, and the second characteristic

7
00:00:31,710 --> 00:00:34,980
is organized around business capabilities.

8
00:00:35,220 --> 00:00:41,790
The microservice approach to division is splitting up into services organized by business capabilities,

9
00:00:42,390 --> 00:00:46,080
and another characteristic is products, not projects.

10
00:00:46,080 --> 00:00:52,560
This is Amazon's notion of you built, you run it, where a developer team takes full responsibility

11
00:00:52,560 --> 00:00:54,330
for the software in production.

12
00:00:55,890 --> 00:00:59,880
And another characteristic is smart endpoints and dumb pipes.

13
00:00:59,880 --> 00:01:05,340
Microservices aim to be decoupled and cohesive as possible.

14
00:01:05,340 --> 00:01:12,090
So they own their own domain logic and receiving a request, applying logic and producing a response

15
00:01:12,090 --> 00:01:13,980
with using RESTful APIs.

16
00:01:15,610 --> 00:01:19,180
And another characteristic is decentralized governance.

17
00:01:19,690 --> 00:01:25,060
For example, Netflix is a good example of an organization that follows this philosophy.

18
00:01:25,090 --> 00:01:32,440
Sharing useful and all tested code as libraries encourage other developers to solve similar problems

19
00:01:32,440 --> 00:01:33,730
in similar ways.

20
00:01:35,760 --> 00:01:42,900
And also decentralized data management, microservices, also decentralized data storage decisions.

21
00:01:42,900 --> 00:01:47,670
We can say this approach as a polyglot, persistence or polyglot databases.

22
00:01:47,670 --> 00:01:54,480
That means microservices prefer letting each service manage its own database, either different instance

23
00:01:54,480 --> 00:01:58,650
of the same database technologies or entirely different database systems.

24
00:02:00,180 --> 00:02:03,570
And another characteristic is infrastructure automation.

25
00:02:03,570 --> 00:02:09,870
That means automate deployment to each new environment and for every microservices with separately.

26
00:02:10,740 --> 00:02:17,670
And we can say that design for failure, microservices design by dealing failures and try to manage

27
00:02:17,670 --> 00:02:22,350
failures with managing errors with proper actions and self-healing mechanisms.

